'''The Helsinki Institute of Physics''' ('''HIP''', {{lang-fi|Fysiikan tutkimuslaitos}}, {{lang-sv|Forskningsinstitutet för fysik}}) is a [[physics]] research institute operated jointly by [[University of Helsinki]], [[Aalto University]], [[University of Jyväskylä]], [[Lappeenranta University of Technology]] and [[Tampere University of Technology]]. The operations of the institute began on September 1, 1996. The foundation of the Institute was provided by the three previous Helsinki-based institutes: SEFT, TFT (University of Helsinki) and HTI (Helsinki University of Technology), which were merged into the new organization. The current director of the institute since 2016 has been prof. [[Paula Eerola]]. The institute is responsible for the [[Finland|Finnish]] research collaboration with [[CERN]].
The research is currently focused on following fields:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hip.fi/?page_id=15|title=Research {{!}} Helsinki Institute of Physics|website=www.hip.fi|access-date=2016-11-30}}</ref> * '''Theory Programme''' ** Nuclear Structure for Weak and Astrophysical Processes ** [[Quantum chromodynamics|QCD]] and Strongly Interacting Gauge Theory ** [[Domain wall (string theory)|Domain Wall]] Dynamics ** [[Physical cosmology|Cosmology]] of the Early and Late Universe ** High Energy [[Phenomenology (particle physics)|Phenomenology]] in the [[Large Hadron Collider|LHC]] Era * '''[[Compact Muon Solenoid|CMS]] Programme''' ** CMS Experiment ** CMS Upgrade ** Tier-2 Operations ** [[TOTEM experiment|TOTEM]] * '''Technology Programme''' ** Accelerator Technology ** Green [[Big data|Big Data]] Project ** Biomedical Imaging ** Novel Instrumentation for Nuclear Safety, Security and Safeguards ** Finnish Business Incubation Center of CERN Technologies * '''Nuclear Matter Programme''' ** [[A Large Ion Collider Experiment|ALICE]] ** [[ISOLDE]] ** [[Facility for Antiproton and Ion Research|FAIR]]
